ing line status and triggering unexpected events, increasing confidence on applied methodologies and easing implantation of these solutions in a near future. With that in mind, aim of this work is, using existing market solutions for overhead line monitoring in combination with community approved mathematical models for dynamic line rating [8]; find solutions which in addition to real time data analysis and predictive line demand estimations, can obtain system's intrinsic parameters based on reverse engineering methodologies and turn those into a source of diagnosis for conductors and metering devices. Therefore, it would make possible early automated countermeasure planning, as well as, conductor detriment tracking, warn operators for conductor replacement or metering device fixing before any malfunctioning is identified; and thus, improve overall functioning by means of simple scheduling. Evaluation of mathematical model adaptability, sensitivity and specificity along with parameter estimation stability encouraged this work that although preliminary shows promising in further development of in-field monitoring solutions for OHL. Main aspects of different explored solutions along these lines take into account computation time, existing software integration feasibility and solution complexity; key aspects for further development and usage of mentioned methodologies. Based on evidence, usage of these parameters in order to observe both conductor behavioural detriments, as well as, malfunctioning of measuring devices, shows plausible although sound evaluation is needed for appropriate event discrimination amongst different possible scenarios. © 2013 CIGRE. All rights reserved.
